The paper deals with predicting the popularity of items in social networks, which involves analyzing the properties of early adopters and their networks. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD), Social and Economic Networks (cs.SOC), Information Retrieval (cs.IR), or Machine Learning (cs.LG). Among these, cs.SI and cs.SD seem to be the most likely categories as they directly deal with social networks and music, respectively. However, the paper also involves machine learning techniques and information retrieval, which makes cs.LG and cs.IR plausible categories as well. Finally, the paper touches upon the problem of understanding why items become popular, which could fall under the category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC).
